Welcome to the=C2=A0200=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined u=
s since last week! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0217,532 sma=
rt, curious folks by subscribing here:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=20
Happy Thursday!=20
Crypto, pronounced dead in 2022, has come back to life. If you=E2=80=99ve b=
een reading Not Boring through that period, you would have known that it wo=
uld come back eventually.=20
But just because token prices are back up doesn=E2=80=99t mean that crypto =
is anywhere close to doing the things that I think it will be able to do. B=
etter infrastructure will need to translate into better applications, which=
 will demand better infrastructure, and on and on. It=E2=80=99s a never-end=
ing project.=20
LayerZero Labs is building foundational infrastructure for crypto all the w=
ay at the foundation=E2=80=A6 LayerZero. It=E2=80=99s an omnichain messagin=
g protocol, a transport layer that allows applications to send messages con=
taining bytes of information from one chain to another. If it succeeds, eac=
h blockchain will be like a node in one larger, more performant network.=20
Today, it=E2=80=99s rolling out v2 of its protocol. I got an early look, an=
d I=E2=80=99m excited to explain what it is and why I think it=E2=80=99s go=
ing to be important. Apologies for the late send =E2=80=94 v2 is hot off th=
e presses [ https://substack.com/redirect/3e8b77c0-10d3-42bf-8536-4c6cac3ae=
201?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
This essay is a Sponsored Deep Dive. While the piece is sponsored, these ar=
e all my real and genuine views. I haven=E2=80=99t written as many of them =
this year as I have before because I=E2=80=99m only writing them on compani=
es that I think have a chance to be really important in an area I care abou=
t, and LayerZero Labs fits that bill.
I=E2=80=99ve been a fan of LayerZero since I had LayerZero Labs CEO Bryan P=
ellegrino on Not Boring Founders in early 2022, and I=E2=80=99m impressed w=
ith the improvements they=E2=80=99ve made in v2 and the potential of the bu=
siness model.=20
You can read more about how I choose which companies to do deep dives on, a=
nd how I write them here [ https://substack.com/redirect/8ff3ed3c-91af-4655=
-9e5d-ef8c1d8fce19?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ].
As always, please, please for the love of God note that this is not investm=
ent advice. LayerZero doesn=E2=80=99t have a token, but it will at some poi=
nt. When that time comes: please do not look back at this piece as investme=
nt advice. If you=E2=80=99re reading this from that future time, please not=
e the following: I am a terrible trader. This is a sponsored piece. a16z, w=
here I=E2=80=99m an advisor, is an investor in LayerZero Labs. I have no id=
ea where ZRO will be priced when trading starts.=20
I just think it=E2=80=99s important infrastructure for crypto, and that cry=
pto infrastructure is important.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
LayerZero: The Language of the Omnichain
In the beginning, there was Bitcoin.=C2=A0
Bitcoin [ https://substack.com/redirect/6f0f5ae3-ddc3-4af9-8e76-22db2bee370=
d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] did =
one thing well. =E2=80=9CA purely peer-to-peer version of electronic cash w=
ould allow online payments to be sent directly from one party to another wi=
thout going through a financial institution.=E2=80=9D
Soon, however, people wanted to do other things peer-to-peer without going =
through institutions.=C2=A0
Enter Ethereum.=C2=A0
Ethereum [ https://substack.com/redirect/07e61945-4b00-4c58-81cb-6f7392887a=
4c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] was=
 designed to do many things. =E2=80=9CWhat Ethereum intends to provide is a=
 blockchain with a built-in fully fledged Turing-complete programming langu=
age that can be used to create =E2=80=98contracts=E2=80=99 that can be used=
 to encode arbitrary state transition functions.=E2=80=9D
With Ethereum, developers could theoretically build all sorts of things on =
blockchains: decentralized applications, domain names, exchanges, lending p=
rotocols, NFTs, DAOs. Turing-complete means that, theoretically, they could=
 build anything onchain.=C2=A0
The challenge was, when they tried to build those things in practice, it wa=
s slow and expensive. When users used those things, it jammed up the system=
 and drove up costs.
So two things happened.=C2=A0
First, right around 2018, a tsunami of new =E2=80=9CLayer 1=E2=80=9D blockc=
hains emerged to either take Ethereum on directly or to focus on doing a sp=
