How LayerZero Works
OK, so how do you build TCP/IP for blockchains? How does LayerZero actually=
 work? What does it do? And if you want to create infrastructure that lasts=
 as long as TCP/IP has, what decisions do you need to make upfront?=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99ll need to get a little technical here, but I=E2=80=99ll try to =
make it as simple as possible for now and then dive into details later.=C2=
=A0
You can think of the LayerZero protocol as a series of pipes that deliver m=
essages between blockchains, transport layer infrastructure that runs below=
 the cities [ https://medium.com/dragonfly-research/blockchains-are-cities-=
564327013f86 ].
These are modern, highly technical pipes. If TCP/IP is plumbing, LayerZero =
is Pipedream [ https://www.pipedreamlabs.co/ ].
Over time, if everything goes just right, these pipes might be the pipes th=
rough which the global economy runs, so the LayerZero Labs team believes th=
at the pipes must have three core characteristics:=C2=A0
Permissionless: Anyone can build on top of LayerZero without approval from =
the team, no matter where they are or what they=E2=80=99re building, and an=
d anyone can run the infrastructure necessary to verify and execute message=
s.=C2=A0
Immutable: Once an endpoint or library is in place, it can=E2=80=99t be cha=
nged, only appended. The protocol will exist in perpetuity, even if develop=
ment on LayerZero stopped today (though breaking changes at the change leve=
l would disrupt endpoints).
Censorship-Resistant: Even if someone had a gun to Bryan=E2=80=99s head, th=
ere would be no way for them to alter a message or prevent it from being se=
nt. Neither governments nor financial institutions looking to front run can=
 ever access a message.=C2=A0
If you don=E2=80=99t think about those three things upfront, Bryan told me,=
 =E2=80=9Cthe whole world will be built on rails that are corruptible.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0
In order to build incorruptible rails that can adapt, extend, and stand the=
 test of time, LayerZero Labs needs to balance security where needed and fl=
exibility where possible.=C2=A0
From the beginning, LayerZero Labs (the developer) split LayerZero (the pro=
tocol) into components ranging from =E2=80=9Ccompletely locked down=E2=80=
=9D to =E2=80=9Cflexible.=E2=80=9D In v2, that split shows up as four compo=
nents:=C2=A0
Endpoints and Validation Libraries are the core of the LayerZero protocol.
Endpoints are low surface-area, open source smart contracts that live on ea=
ch chain and can=E2=80=99t be changed once they=E2=80=99re in place. Valida=
tion Libraries are responsible for sending packets from one chain and valid=
ating them on the other and define how communication should be handled on e=
ach chain.=C2=A0
They=E2=80=99re the immutable pipes through which messages flow.=C2=A0
Verification and execution of messages are up to the application to decide;=
 they can hook any set of verifiers and any executor they choose into the p=
rotocol.=C2=A0
Verification provides the security for the messages being sent; some entity=
 or entities verify that each message is legitimate. Execution essentially =
means paying gas so that smart contracts on each end can process the transa=
ction described in the messages.=C2=A0
In v1, verification and execution were provided by Oracles and Relayers. In=
 v2, they=E2=80=99re provided by Decentralized Verifier Networks (DVNs) and=
 Executors.=C2=A0
Importantly, in v2, LayerZero Labs has totally decoupled security from exec=
ution in order to guarantee censorship-resistance without impacting livenes=
s, or the ability of the protocol to continue functioning and processing tr=
ansactions without interruption. You don=E2=80=99t want anyone to be able t=
o mess with your messages, and you always want them to go through.=C2=A0
Don=E2=80=99t worry. I=E2=80=99ll explain what all of this means in detail.=
 Getting there is going to take a journey through LayerZero=E2=80=99s histo=
ry, the theory and practice of LayerZero v1, and the why behind the v2 upgr=
ades.=C2=A0
What hasn=E2=80=99t changed between v1 and v2 is that endpoints are immutab=
le and validation libraries are append-only. The deepest layers of the prot=
ocol remain unchanged, because they were built to be unchangeable from the =
beginning.=C2=A0
Security and execution are still modular and up to the application, too, bu=
t what has changed in v2 is exactly how that happens. To understand that, w=
e need to understand why it was harder for applications to choose in practi=
ce than it was in theory.=C2=A0
