aiting for a painfully long time. More than once, I=E2=80=99ve worried if m=
y tokens were lost forever while I waited.=C2=A0
At launch, Bryan did a video comparing LayerZero to bridges that shows how =
slow bridging can be:=C2=A0
So the trio realized that they=E2=80=99d need to go deeper into the stack t=
o solve the problem. They=E2=80=99d need to build foundational infrastructu=
re on top of which bridges could be built. They=E2=80=99d need to build a p=
rotocol that would transport arbitrary messages across blockchains.=C2=A0
LayerZero was born.=C2=A0
By building a messaging protocol instead of a bridge, LayerZero Labs elimin=
ated the idea of locking and wrapping tokens, got rid of the honeypot, bund=
led a bunch of steps into one message, and removed the need to worry about =
gas.=C2=A0
Chain A sends a message containing bytes to Chain B, and Chain B executes w=
hatever instructions are contained in the bytes.=C2=A0
For times when that message contains instructions to transfer tokens, Layer=
Zero Labs introduced the Omnichain Fungible Token [ https://layerzero.gitbo=
ok.io/docs/evm-guides/layerzero-omnichain-contracts ] (OFT) Standard. Accor=
ding to the docs, =E2=80=9CThis standard works by burning tokens on the sou=
rce chain whenever an omnichain transfer is initiated, sending a message vi=
a the protocol and delivering a function call to the destination contract t=
o mint the same number of tokens burned, creating a unified supply across b=
oth networks.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
With OFT, there is no pot of tokens sitting somewhere =E2=80=93 tokens are =
burned on one side and re-minted on the other.=C2=A0
LayerZero launched on St. Patrick=E2=80=99s Day, March 17, 2022. Alongside =
the launch, the LayerZero Founders built a bridge, Stargate [ https://starg=
ateprotocol.gitbook.io/stargate/ ], to show it off. (It=E2=80=99s now gover=
ned by a DAO.) Stargate uses the LayerZero protocol to move native assets i=
