-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Each L1 and L2 &#8211; the serious ones=
, at least &#8211; attempts to improve on Ethereum in one or more ways. The=
y might be faster, cheaper, more scalable, more private, or more custom-bui=
lt for specific use cases, from DeFi to payments to NFTs.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">If you think that sounds confusing, imagine what it feels like fo=
r a user trying to figure out where to do things onchain. Worse, imagine wh=
at it&#8217;s like for a developer trying to figure out which chain to buil=
d on!</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If you want to build an application that uses cr=
ypto, there&#8217;s all sorts of complexity and trade-offs you have to make=
=2E Do you want to build something that=
&#8217;s cheaper and faster? Cool, if=20=
you do, it might be less secure and there may be fewer users and less liqui=
dity on that faster, cheaper chain.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64,=
 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>All to=
ld, there are </span><em>hundreds</em><span> of Layer 1s and Layer 2s. Each=
 makes different trade-offs, each has strengths and weaknesses. And each, f=
or all intents and purposes, operates in a silo.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">If you view each blockchain as its own competing network, it&#821=
7;s a messy state of affairs: confusing for users, brutal for developers, a=
nd results in fragmented user bases and liquidity.&#160;</p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;">I don&#8217;t think that&#8217;s the right way to view blockchains thoug=
h.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In May 2021&#8217;s </span><em><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/755318f7-519a-4744-9c57-6f4fa7a45593?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">Own The Internet</=
a><span>, </span></em><span>I wrote:</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-=
left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rg=
b(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; marg=
in-left: 20px;"><em><span>There are a lot of Something Maxis, people who be=
lieve their thing is the one and only solution, but I subscribe to the idea=
 that </span><strong>each successful L1 or L2 will focus on what it does be=
st and interoperate with others who do something else best</strong><span>. =
I&#8217;m a Maximalist Minimalist.</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;"><strong>I think the right way to view blockchains is as nodes in one =
larger Omnichain network.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In that view, compe=
titors become complements. Each chain can focus on doing one thing really, =
really well. As more chains enter the fray, instead of becoming more confus=
ing and fragmented, the Omnichain becomes more capable.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">It&#8217;s a nice idea, if you just assume that all the chains ca=
n easily interoperate. But they don&#8217;t. Go try bridging tokens from on=
e chain to another if you don&#8217;t believe me. Blockchains don&#8217;t n=
atively communicate with each other; many don&#8217;t even speak the same l=
anguage.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">What&#8217;s needed in this world is a way fo=
r all of these nodes to speak with each other swiftly and securely. What&#8=
217;s needed is a common language for the Omnichain.&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;"><strong><span>That&#8217;s what </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com=
/redirect/0a1ac2f4-616e-44ad-98aa-61175399e73c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64)=
; text-decoration: underline;">LayerZero</a><span> Labs is building.</span>=
</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">LayerZero Labs is the company developing the=
 LayerZero protocol, an open-source messaging protocol that allows develope=
rs to build omnichain, interoperable applications. Messaging here doesn&#82=
17;t mean SMS &#8211; it means sending any arbitrary packet of bytes from o=
ne chain to another, so that a smart contract on Chain A can tell a smart c=
