 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">What exa=
ctly does TCP/IP do? Miller continues:&#160;</p><blockquote style=3D"border=
-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; mar=
gin-left: 20px;"><em><strong>TCP/IP is a set of protocols that enable commu=
nication between computers.</strong><span> There was a time when it was not=
 important for computers to communicate with each other. There was no need =
for a common protocol. But as computers became networked, the need arose fo=
r computers to agree on certain protocols.</span></em></p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; =
margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>Today, a network administrator can choose fro=
m many protocols, but </span><strong>the TCP/IP protocol is the most widely=
 used</strong><span>. Part of the reason is that TCP/IP is the protocol of =
choice on the Internet&#8212;the world&#8217;s largest network. If you want=
 a computer to communicate on the Internet, it&#8217;ll have to use TCP/IP.=
</span></em></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><strong>Another re=
ason for TCP/IP&#8217;s popularity is that it is compatible with almost eve=
ry computer in the world.</strong><span> The TCP/IP stack is supported by c=
urrent versions of all the major operating systems and network operating sy=
stems&#8212;including Windows 95/98, Windows NT, Windows 2000, Windows XP, =
Linux, Unix, and NetWare.</span></em></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px=
;"><em><span>Unlike proprietary protocols developed by hardware and softwar=
e vendors to make their equipment work, </span><strong>TCP/IP enjoys suppor=
