 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Endpoints ar=
e low surface-area, open source smart contracts that live on each chain and=
 can&#8217;t be changed once they&#8217;re in place. Validation Libraries a=
re responsible for sending packets from one chain and validating them on th=
e other and define how communication should be handled on each chain.&#160;=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">They&#8217;re the immutable pipes through which messa=
ges flow.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Verification</strong><span> an=
d </span><strong>execution</strong><span> of messages are up to the applica=
tion to decide; they can hook any set of verifiers and any executor they ch=
oose into the protocol.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Verificatio=
n provides the security for the messages being sent; some entity or entitie=
s </span><em>verify</em><span> that each message is legitimate. Execution e=
ssentially means paying gas so that smart contracts on each end can process=
 the transaction described in the messages.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;"><span>In v1, verification and execution were provided by Oracles and Rel=
ayers. In v2, they&#8217;re provided by </span><strong>Decentralized Verifi=
er Networks (DVNs)</strong><span> and </span><strong>Executors</strong><spa=
n>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Importantly, in v2, LayerZero L=
abs has totally </span><strong>decoupled security from execution in order t=
o guarantee censorship-resistance without impacting liveness, </strong><spa=
n>or the ability of the protocol to continue functioning and processing tra=
nsactions without interruption. You don&#8217;t want anyone to be able to m=
ess with your messages, and you always want them to go through.&#160;</span=
></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Don&#8217;t worry. I&#8217;ll explain what all of th=
is means in detail. Getting there is going to take a journey through LayerZ=
ero&#8217;s history, the theory and practice of LayerZero v1, and the why b=
ehind the v2 upgrades.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>What </span><em>has=
n&#8217;t</em><span> changed between v1 and v2 is that endpoints are immuta=
ble and validation libraries are append-only. </span><strong>The deepest la=
yers of the protocol remain unchanged, because they were built to be unchan=
geable from the beginning.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64,=
 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Securi=
ty and execution are still modular and up to the application, too, but what=
 </span><em>has</em><span> changed in v2 is exactly how that happens. To un=
derstand that, we need to understand why it was harder for applications to =
choose in practice than it was in theory.&#160;</span></p><h3 class=3D"head=
er-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-o=
sx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -we=
bkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rg=
b(64, 64, 64); font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSy=
stemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Em=
oji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight:=
 bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><=
strong>LayerZero v1: From Bridges to Oracles and Relayers&#160;&#160;</stro=
ng></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">LayerZero started out as a side project for Bryan=
, Ryan Zarick, and Caleb Banister.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, =
64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>After l=
eaving a successful poker career behind in 2014, Bryan kept his brain spinn=
ing on a </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/ed905368-02c4-4308=
-abb3-e1a1af9a9462?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline=
;">series of hard projects</a><span>. He tried bitcoin mining in 2014, buil=
t an AI model to measure pitchers&#8217; performance that he sold to MLB te=
ams in 2016, launched a platform to let people launch their own tokens, Ope=
nToken, in 2018, and built the world&#8217;s best poker AI, </span><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/add278ef-12a8-4bb7-b1cf-496b334dac3a?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">Supremus</a><span>=
, with Ryan, Caleb, and Meta AI researcher Noam Brown (the creator of </spa=
n><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/e72ebb5c-d010-4ccb-a1c8-f4651a24=
111d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" re=
l style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">CICERO</a><=
span>) in 2020.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>&#8220;All my life,=
 I&#8217;ve just liked to work on hard problems,&#8221; he told an </span><=
a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/ed905368-02c4-4308-abb3-e1a1af9a946=
2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">interviewer fo=
r Sequoia</a><span>. &#8220;More than anything else, that&#8217;s what attr=
acts me.&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Later in 2020, when Binance Sma=
rt Chain launched and started to pick up real adoption, a rarity then among=
 non-Bitcoin or Ethereum chains, he got the band back together. Bryan, Ryan=
, and Caleb built a game in which gladiators fought to the death on the che=
aper, faster BSC, the winning gladiator was minted as an NFT, and the NFT w=
as stored on the more secure Ethereum. It was a toy model to test the chain=
s, and the test was fruitful.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In the proce=
ss of moving the NFT from BSC to Ethereum, they hit a problem: </span><stro=
ng>bridges</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Just as physical bri=
dges connect two landmasses, bridges connect two blockchains. They&#8217;re=
 how you send tokens &#8211; fungible or NFT &#8211; between chains.&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Because different chains have different ways of doing =
things, a token that works on one might not work on the other. So if you wa=
nted to send your tokens from say, Ethereum to Polygon, in order to use an =
app on Polygon, you&#8217;d go to a bridge and the bridge would do a few th=
ings:</p><ol style=3D"margin-top: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px =
0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: =
4px;"><strong>Lock the Original Asset.</strong><span> Essentially, the brid=
ge sends your ETH to a smart contract that holds it &#8220;securely.&#8221;=
&#160;</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-s=
izing: border-box; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Create a Wrapp=
ed Version. </strong><span>The bridge issues a &#8220;wrapped&#8221; versio=
n of your ETH, WETH, that represents your original ETH but works with Polyg=
on&#8217;s rules.</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p sty=
le=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Giv=
e You the Wrapped Version. </strong><span>The bridge puts the WETH in your =
wallet on Polygon, which you can use to do things on Polygon.&#160;</span><=
/p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-=
box; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0;=
 margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Redeem the Original Asset. <=
/strong><span>To redeem your original ETH on Ethereum, you send your WETH b=
ack to the bridge, the bridge burns it, unlocks your original ETH, and puts=
 it in your Ethereum wallet, where you can use it to do things on Ethereum.=
&#160;</span></p></li></ol><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">As Bryan, Ryan, and Caleb disc=
overed, though, Bridges have a couple of major problems.</p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;"><span>First, they&#8217;re a </span><strong>security nightmare</strong><=
span>. All of that locked ETH (or whatever locked token) is a gigantic flas=
hing sign that there&#8217;s a pot of money hackers can try to break into. =
In 2022, hackers exploited the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redir=
ect/faa1f9e5-083e-4a70-9f9a-b400ddaa1786?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text=
-decoration: underline;">Wormhole Bridge between Solana and Ethereum for $3=
26 million</a><span> and the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirec=
t/07b74c35-ce7f-4022-b55e-80303fb61aba?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-d=
ecoration: underline;">Ronin Bridge between Ronin and Ethereum for $624 mil=
lion</a><span>. The US Treasury Department alleged that the North Korean ha=
cking group Lazarus was behind the Ronin hack, highlighting that these syst=
ems need to be robust against state-level actors.&#160;</span></p><div clas=
s=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
